38. To render this theory more intelligible, the Doctor informs the ignorant reader,P. 77. 
               "that there is a perpetual intercourſe betwixt the blood veſſels and the cellular membrane, and conſequently between the contents of both, the blood and fat."—It is ſomewhat ſingular, that this poiſoned fat ſhould, in its paſſage to the liver, mix with the blood without injuring that fluid, which throughout the entire progreſs of the diſeaſe is found to differ in nothing from that of a perſon in health. This obſtacle was too obvious to eſcape the Doctor;

but he tumbles over it very clumſily: he ſuppoſes, notwithſtanding appearances, that the blood muſt be ultimately vitiated by the bile; ſo that the blood firſt vitiates the bile, and the bile returns the compliment to the blood.
